enomenon of the “country place” as a focus for examining the relationships between urban and rural life, between building and the natural environment, and between architectural design and social, cultural, economic, and political forces. “The villa,” he reminds us, “accommodates a fantasy which is impervious to reality.” As city dwellers idealized country life, the villa, unlike the farmhouse, became associated with pleasure and asserted its modernity and status as a product of the architect’s imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aCountry homes. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  aAusten, Jane.  aAvezzano: relief from 8.  aBembo, Pietro.  aBoyle, Richard.  aBurlington, Richard Boyle.  aCampania.  aCanaletto.  aCato.  aClaude Lorrain.  aDaly, César.  aHorace.  aJames, Henry.  aJefferson, Thomas.  aLaurentinum.  aLe Corbusier.  aMonet, Claude.  aMonticello, Va.  aPembroke.  aPliny the Younger.  aPoliziano, Angelo.  aPope, Alexander.  aRome.  aSchinkel, Karl Friedrich.  aShaftesbury.  aThomson, James.  aTivoli: Hadrian’s villa.  aTurner, Joseph Mallord William.  aTusci.  aVarro, Marcus Terentius.  aVirgil.  aVitruvius.  aWharton, Edith.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertThe A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Packagez978311129290840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691252322?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691252322423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691252322/original  a978-3-11-129290-8  The A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles